ks?id=cGHGPgj1_tIC |title=The Dark Side of Democracy: Explaining Ethnic Cleansing|isbn=9780521538541}}\n* {{cite book|last=Mincheva & Gurr|first=Lyubov Grigorova, Ted Robert|ref=Mincheva & Gurr|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=vFNwrdnzQq0C |title=Crime-Terror Alliances and the State: Ethnonationalist and Islamist Challenges to Regional Security|isbn=9780415506489}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Nigel|ref=Thomas|year=2006|publisher=Osprey Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7cOQ9Nch2AC |title=The Yugoslav Wars (2): Bosnia, Kosovo And Macedonia 1992\u20132001|isbn=9781841769646}}\n\n===Media===\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/kosovo/ War in Europe] [[PBS Frontline]]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/kosovo_fact_files/default.stm Kosovo fact files] [[BBC News]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20000815075301/http://www.cnn.com/SPECIALS/1998/10/kosovo/ Focus on Kosovo] [[CNN]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCHTK-2W11Vh1V4uwofOfR4w/search?query=kosovo Kosovo War on AP Video Archive] [[Associated Press]]\n\n===Maps===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040111054136/http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/kosovo.html Maps of Kosovo, Perry\u2013Casta\u00f1eda Library Map Collection]\n\n{{Post-Cold War European conflicts}}\n{{Kosovo topics}}\n{{Yugoslavia topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Kosovo War| ]]\n[[Category:1998 in Kosovo]]\n[[Category:1999 in Kosovo]]\n[[Category:History of Kosovo]]\n[[Category:Ethnic cleansing in Europe]]\n[[Category:Albania\u2013Serbia relations]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1998]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1999]]\n", "name_user": "Mozad655", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUN, NATO, and OSCE (1998\u20131999):Changed language to more neutral form.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kosovo_War"}
{"title_page": "Hammer DeRoburt", "text_new": "{{short description|President of Nauru}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name                = Hammer DeRoburt\n|image               = Hammer DeRoburt.jpg\n|imagesize           =  \n|smallimage          = \n|caption             = Hammer DeRoburt, 1968\n|order               = [[President of Nauru]]\n|term_start          = 31 January 1968\n|term_end            = 22 December 1976\n|deputy              = [[Buraro Detudamo]]\n|predecessor         = First President\n|successor           = [[Bernard Dowiyogo]]\n|term_start2          = 15 May 1978\n|term_end2            = 17 September 1986\n|deputy2              = [[Buraro Detudamo]]\n|predecessor2         = [[Lagumot Harris]]\n|successor2           = [[Kennan Adeang]]\n|term_start3          = 1 October 1986\n|term_end3            = 12 December 1986\n|deputy3              = [[Buraro Detudamo]]\n|predecessor3         = [[Kennan Adeang]]\n|successor3           = [[Kennan Adeang]]\n|term_start4          = 22 December 1986\n|term_end4            = 17 August 1989\n|deputy4              = [[Buraro Detudamo]]\n|predecessor4         = [[Kennan Adeang]]\n|successor4           = [[Kenos Aroi]]\n|constituency_MP5 = [[Boe Constituency|Boe]]\n|parliament5 = Nauruan\n|predecessor5 = '''New title'''\n|successor5 = [[Michael Aroi]]\n|term_start5 = 31 January 1968\n|term_end5 = 15 July 1992\n|birth_date          = 25 September 1922\n|birth_place         =  [[Nauru]]\n|death_date          = 15 July 1992 (aged 69)\n|death_place         = [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]\n|constituency        = \n|party               = \n|spouse              = \n|children            = \n|profession          = \n|signature           = \n|footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Sir. Hammer DeRoburt [[OBE]], [[GCMG]]''' (25 September 1922 &ndash; 15 July 1992) was the founding [[President of Nauru|President]] of the Republic of [[Nauru]], and ruled the country for most of its first twenty years of independence.\n\n==Background and early career==\nBorn 1922, DeRoburt was the grandson of a former Head Chief of Nauru and also had [[Banaba Island|Banaban]] heritage, as his grandmother was from the island.<ref name=NV1>Nancy Viviani (1970) ''Nauru: Phosphate and Political Progress'' Australian National University Press, p. 107</ref> After being educated on Nauru, he attended the [[Gordon Institute of TAFE|Gordon Institute of Technology]] in [[Geelong]], [[Australia]].<ref name=NV1/> After returning to Nauru, he started working as a teacher.<ref name=NV1/>\n\nDuring [[Japanese occupation of Nauru]] he was deported to [[Chuuk Lagoon|Truk]] by the Japanese, along with most of the Nauruan population. When he returned to Nauru in 1946 he started working at the Department of Education.<ref name=NV1/> He decided to stand in the [[1951 Nauruan Local Government Council election|first elections]] to the [[Local Government Council]] in 1951, and although he gained enough support to be nominated as a candidate in the [[Boe District|Boe]] constituency, he was disqualified due to irregularities in his nomination.<ref name=NV2>Viviani, p108</ref> Local residents and European residents protested without success, whilst a petition to the 1953 Visiting Mission from the United Nations was also overlooked.<ref name=NV2/>\n\nIn [[1955 Nauruan Local Government Council election|1955 elections]] he stood again in the Boe constituency and was elected to the Council.<ref name=NV1/> In 1956 the Council elected him Head Chief.<ref name=NV2/>\n\n==Presidency of post-independence Nauru==\n[[File:South_Pacific_Forum,_August_5,_1971,_Wellington_(19969820699).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|[[Pacific Islands Forum|DeRobert at the Pacific Islands Forum]], August 5, 1971, [[Wellington]]]]\nDeRoburt led the country to independence on 31 January 1968 and was president for most of the period until 17 August 1989. In December 1976, younger politicians gained a majority and installed [[Bernard Dowiyogo]] as president, but DeRoburt returned to power in May 1978. He was also out of office for two short periods in September and December 1986.\n\n==Personal==\nHe was given an honorary knighthood by Queen [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Elizabeth II]] in 1982.\n\nDeRoburt is credited with introducing [[Australian rules football]] to Nauru, which became the [[national sport]].\n\nHe died in [[Melbourne]] in 1992 from diabetes mellitus.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-new | reason=Independence of Nauru}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[President of Nauru]] | years=31 January 1968 \u2013 22 December 1976}}\n{{S-aft | after=[[Bernard Dowiyogo]]}}\n{{S-bef | before=[[Lagumot Harris]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[President of Nauru]] | years=15 May 1978 \u2013 17 September 1986}}\n{{S-aft | after=[[Kennan Adeang]]}}\n{{S-bef | before=[[Kennan Adeang]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[President of Nauru]] | years=1 October 1986\u2013December 1986}}\n{{S-aft | after=[[Kennan Adeang]]}}\n{{S-bef | before=[[Kennan Adeang]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[President of Nauru]] | years=December 1986\u201317 August 1989}}\n{{S-aft | after=[[Kenos Aroi]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NauruPres}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deroburt, Hammer}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:People from Boe District]]\n[[Category:Nauruan educators]]\n[[Category:People deported from Nauru]]\n[[Category:Nauruan civil servants]]\n[[Category:Head Chiefs of Nauru]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Nauru]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Nauru]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|President of Nauru}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name                = Hammer DeRoburt\n|image               = Hammer DeRoburt.jpg\n|imagesize           =  \n|smallimage          = \n|caption             = Hammer DeRoburt, 1968\n|order               = [[President of Nauru]]\n|term_start          = 31 January 1968\n|term_end            = 22 December 1976\n|deputy              = [[Buraro Detudamo]]\n|predecessor         = First President\n|successor           = [[Bernard Dowiyogo]]\n|term_start2          = 15 May 1978\n|term_end2            = 17 September 1986\n|deputy2              = [[Buraro Detudamo]]\n|predecessor2         = [[Lagumot Harris]]\n|successor2           = [[Kennan Adeang]]\n|term_start3          = 1 October 1986\n|term_end3            = 12 December 1986\n|deputy3              = [[Buraro Detudamo]]\n|predecessor3         = [[Kennan Adeang]]\n|successor3           = [[Kennan Adeang]]\n|term_start4          = 22 December 1986\n|term_end4            = 17 August 1989\n|deputy4              = [[Buraro Detudamo]]\n|predecessor4         = [[Kennan Adeang]]\n|successor4           = [[Kenos Aroi]]\n|constituency_MP5 = [[Boe Constituency|Boe]]\n|parliament5 = Nauruan\n|predecessor5 = '''New title'''\n|successor5 = [[Michael Aroi]]\n|term_start5 = 31 January 1968\n|term_end5 = 15 July 1992\n|birth_date          = 25 September 1922\n|birth_place         =  [[Nauru]]\n|death_date          = 15 July 1992 (aged 69)\n|death_place         = [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]\n|constituency        = \n|party               = \n|spouse              = \n|children            = \n|profession          = \n|signature           = \n|footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Sir. Hammer DeRoburt [[OBE]], [[GCMG]]''' (25 September 1922 &ndash; 15 July 1992) was the founding [[President of Nauru|President]] of the Republic of [[Nauru]], and ruled the country for most of its first twenty years of independence.\n\n==Background and early career==\nBorn 1922, DeRoburt was the grandson of a former Head Chief of Nauru and also had [[Banaba Island|Banaban]] heritage, as his grandmother was from the island.<ref name=NV1>Nancy Viviani (1970) ''Nauru: Phosphate and Political Progress'' Australian National University Press, p. 107</ref> After being educated on Nauru, he attended the [[Gordon Institute of TAFE|Gordon Institute of Technology]] in [[Geelong]], [[Australia]].<ref name=NV1/> After returning to Nauru, he started working as a teacher.<ref name=NV1/>\n\nDuring [[Japanese occupation of Nauru]] he was deported to [[Chuuk Lagoon|Truk]] by the Japanese, along with most of the Nauruan population. When he returned to Nauru in 1946 he started working at the Department of Education.<ref name=NV1/> He decided to stand in the [[1951 Nauruan Local Government Council election|first elections]] to the [[Local Government Council]] in 1951, and although he gained enough support to be nominated as a candidate in the [[Boe District|Boe]] constituency, he was disqualified due to irregularities in his nomination.<ref name=NV2>Viviani, p108</ref> Local residents and European residents protested without success, whilst a petition to the 1953 Visiting Mission from the United Nations was also overlooked.<ref name=NV2/>\n\nIn [[1955 Nauruan Local Government Council election|1955 elections]] he stood again in the Boe constituency and was elected to the Council.<ref name=NV1/> In 1956 the Council elected him Head Chief.<ref name=NV2/>\n\n==Presidency of post-independence Nauru==\nDeRoburt led the country to independence on 31 January 1968 and was president for most of the period until 17 August 1989. In December 1976, younger politicians gained a majority and installed [[Bernard Dowiyogo]] as president, but DeRoburt returned to power in May 1978. He was also out of office for two short periods in September and December 1986.\n\n==Personal==\nHe was given an honorary knighthood by Queen [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Elizabeth II]] in 1982.\n\nDeRoburt is credited with introducing [[Australian rules football]] to Nauru, which became the [[national sport]].\n\nHe died in [[Melbourne]] in 1992 from diabetes mellitus.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-new | reason=Independence of Nauru}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[President of Nauru]] | years=31 January 1968 \u2013 22 December 1976}}\n{{S-aft | after=[[Bernard Dowiyogo]]}}\n{{S-bef | before=[[Lagumot Harris]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[President of Nauru]] | years=15 May 1978 \u2013 17 September 1986}}\n{{S-aft | after=[[Kennan Adeang]]}}\n{{S-bef | before=[[Kennan Adeang]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[President of Nauru]] | years=1 October 1986\u2013December 1986}}\n{{S-aft | after=[[Kennan Adeang]]}}\n{{S-bef | before=[[Kennan Adeang]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[President of Nauru]] | years=December 1986\u201317 August 1989}}\n{{S-aft | after=[[Kenos Aroi]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NauruPres}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deroburt, Hammer}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:People from Boe District]]\n[[Category:Nauruan educators]]\n[[Category:People deported from Nauru]]\n[[Category:Nauruan civil servants]]\n[[Category:Head Chiefs of Nauru]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Nauru]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Nauru]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n", "name_user": "MagicPie97", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePresidency of post-independence Nauru:Added Image from Wiki Commons", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hammer_DeRoburt"}
{"title_page": "Gordon Curran Stewart", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name= Gordon Stewart\n| birth_name= Gordon Curran Stewart\n| birth_date= July 22, 1939\n| birth_place= [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date = November 26, 2014 (aged 75)\n| death_place = [[Garrison, New York]], U.S.<ref name=\"death\">[http://philipstown.info/2014/11/28/gordon-stewart-founder-gone Notice of death of Gordon C. Stewart], philipstown.info, November 28, 2014; accessed December 12, 2014.</ref>\n| education= [[University of Chicago Laboratory Schools]], [[Oberlin College#College of Arts & Sciences|Oberlin College of Arts and Sciences]], [[University of Chicago]], [[University of Vienna]], [[Yale School of Drama]]\n| occupation= Vice Chairman of the International Insurance Society, Publisher of the Philipstown Dot Info Newspaper, Founder of The Next Deal, Inc.\n| known_for= Deputy Chief Speechwriter to President Carter 1978\u20131981, Vice President of American Stock Exchange 1982\u20131989, President of Insurance Information Institute 1991\u20132006, North American Liaison for The Geneva Association 1995\u20132012, and Vice Chairman of the International Insurance Society 2012\u2013present.\n|spouse= Zanne Early (1995\u20132014; his death) \n|children =1}}\n\n'''Gordon Curran Stewart''' (July 22, 1939 \u2013 November 26, 2014)<ref name=\"death\"/> was an American speechwriter, academic, businessman and publisher.\n\nStewart was:\n* Deputy Chief Speechwriter to [[Jimmy Carter|President Jimmy Carter]]<ref>[https://newrepublic.com/tags/gordon-stewart Profile], newrepublic.com; accessed November 28, 2014.</ref>\n* President of the [[Insurance Information Institute]]<ref>[http://www.iii.org/press-release/gordon-stewart-to-retire-from-iii-december-31robert-p-hartwig-to-become-president-071106 \"Gordon Stewart profile], iii.org, Insurance Information Institute website; accessed November 28, 2014.</ref>\n* North American Liaison for [[The Geneva Association]]\n* Chairman of The Geneva Association Communications Council\n* Executive for Policy and Programs to New York Mayor [[John Lindsay]]\n* Head of Public Affairs for [[Arthur Levitt]] at the [[American Stock Exchange]]\n* Member of the [[Defense Science Board]]\n\nHe wrote on political and economic topics for the [[International Association for the Study of Insurance Economics]], ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[US News & World Report]]'', and [[CNN]].\n\n==Early life==\nStewart was born in Chicago in 1939 to Henry Stewart and Evangeline (n\u00e9e Williams) Stewart. His father was born in Scotland and emigrated to the United States at the age of 26, where he became a Presbyterian minister and social worker/organizer in the Chicago neighborhoods. Stewart's mother, Evangeline, worked as a [[University of Chicago]] librarian, and this, coupled with the help of a scholarship, allowed Stewart to enter the [[University of Chicago Laboratory Schools]], where he remained into his high school years and where he was student body president. {{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n==Education==\nStewart received his Bachelor of Arts degree from the [[Oberlin College#College of Arts & Sciences|Oberlin College of Arts and Sciences]] (as the full four-year George F. Baker Scholar having been accepted at the age of 16), where he focused on history and music.  He returned to the University of Chicago to work on a PhD. in European History.  He studied music and drama at the [[University of Vienna]] in Austria, and then received an MFA in Directing from [[Yale School of Drama]]. In his last year at the Yale School of Drama, he was admitted as a doctoral candidate in comparative literature, which led to his first position as an instructor of English and theatre at [[Amherst College]]. {{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n==Career==\n\n===Pre-White House===\nStewart's first political job was as a ten-year-old poll-watcher in Chicago's 5th Ward which staunchly but futilely opposed the political machine of [[Richard J. Daley]]. His next was at the University of Chicago Laboratory Schools where he was student body president. As a student at [[Oberlin College]], he won its only all-school election, and spent several months traveling in and writing about West Africa in the days before the [[Peace Corps]] was founded. He left teaching at [[Amherst College]] to begin a career in drama and politics in New York. While he was directing plays, he worked as Director of Communications for Business Communications for the Arts. There he wrote his first article for a noted public figure, former US Treasury Secretary [[C. Douglas Dillon]], followed by speeches for [[Katharine Graham]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[William S. Paley]] of [[CBS]], and [[Arnold Gingrich]], the founder of ''Esquire Magazine'', who introduced him to New York Mayor [[John Lindsay]], which led to his position as Chief Speechwriter and Executive Assistant to the Mayor from 1971\u201373. {{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nFollowing his time in City Hall, Stewart was Director of Policy for [[Howard J. Samuels]]'s run for the Governorship of New York in 1974, and also wrote speeches for other [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] campaigns, including [[Jimmy Carter]]'s successful run for the Presidency of the United States in 1976. During this time, Stewart also wrote and directed theatre in New York and London.<ref>John Willis, ''Theatre World, #134, Crown Publishers, 1977.<!-- ISBN/ISSN, page(s) needed --></ref>\n\nHe worked as a screenwriter in Los Angeles, where he became a lifelong friend of [[Philip Dunne (writer)|Philip Ives Dunne]], the first screenwriter to receive a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], and a strong and vocal opponent of the [[Hollywood blacklist|Hollywood Blacklisting]] of the 1950s. Stewart gave the dedication speech for the [https://web.archive.org/web/20130407173125/http://www.wga.org/theater/theater.html Writer's Guild Theatre] when it was named in Dunne's honor.\n\nIn Hollywood, Stewart was asked to direct '''[[The Elephant Man (play)|The Elephant Man]]'' in its Broadway debut in New York.<ref name=\"Mattson\">Kevin Mattson, \"What the Heck Are You Up To, Mr. President? Jimmy Carter, America's \"Malaise\", and the Speech That Should Have Changed the Country\" (Bloomsbury, 2009)</ref> Soon after, he was appointed Deputy Chief Speechwriter to [[Jimmy Carter|President Carter]].<ref name=\"death\"/>\n\n===White House===\nCarter's Chief Speechwriter [[Hendrik Hertzberg]] invited Stewart to join the White House in 1978 as the President's Deputy Chief Speechwriter.<ref>\"Presidential Speechwriting\", pp. 169\u201388 (Kurt Ritter, ed., Texas A&M University Press, 2003).</ref><ref name=\"RobertSchlesinger\">Robert Schlesinger, ''White House Ghosts, Presidents and their Speechwriters from FDR to George W. Bush'' (Simon & Schuster, 2008), pp. 301\u201304.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref><ref name=\"mattson\">Kevin Mattson, ''\"What the Heck Are You Up To, Mr. President? Jimmy Carter, America's 'Malaise', and the Speech That Should Have Changed the Country\"'' (Bloomsbury, 2009), pp. 63\u201364.<!-- ISBN/ISSN needed --></ref> Stewart collaborated with Hertzberg on virtually all the major speeches of the Carter Presidency from 1978 onwards, including the landmark presidential address, the [[Oval Office]] [[Malaise speech|\"Crisis of Confidence\" talk of July 15, 1979]].<ref name=\"Mattson\"/><ref name=\"RobertSchlesinger\"/><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/15/opinion/15stewart.html Gordon Stewart, ''Carter's Speech Therapy''], ''The New York Times'', July 14, 2009.</ref>\n\nStewart was directly involved in multiple Presidential projects including the [[Strategic Arms Limitation Talks]] (SALT II), energy, fiscal and monetary policy, human rights issues, the response to the [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan]], the first visit to the White House by a Pope in United States history by [[Pope John Paul II]] in 1979, three State of the Union addresses, and the farewell speech of President Carter to the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmycarterlibrary.gov/documents/speeches/farewell.phtml|title=President Jimmy Carter's Farewell Address|publisher=Jimmycarterlibrary.gov|accessdate=2014-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211221648/http://www.jimmycarterlibrary.gov/documents/speeches/farewell.phtml|archive-date=2013-12-11|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Post White House===\nFollowing his time in the White House, Stewart continued his work in politics as a director of the [[New York Urban Coalition]], and as an advisor to various business, government, and academic forums including the [[Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget]], the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], the American Business Conference in Washington DC the [[International Commission for Central American Recovery and Development]], the [[Council on Competitiveness]], and the [[Defence Science Board]].<ref>\"The Report on the International Commission for Central American Recovery\", page ix, Duke University, 1989.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref><ref>Sally Bedell Smith, ''The Life of Pamela Churchill Harriman'', p. 355, Simon & Schuster, 1996.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref>\n\n===American Stock Exchange===\nFrom 1982\u201389, Stewart served as Vice President of the [[American Stock Exchange]] under [[Arthur Levitt Jr.]]<ref>Arthur Levitt & Gordon Stewart, \"Can American Business Compete?\", ''GLOBAL COMPETIVENESS: GETTING THE U.S. BACK ON TRACK'', pp. 271\u2013298 (Martin K. Starr ed., Norton 1988)</ref><ref>Daniel Yergin, ''Global Insecurity'' (Houghton Mifflin, 1982); {{ISBN|9780395305171}} (back cover citation)<!-- page(s) needed --></ref>  Responsible for the external affairs of the Exchange, Stewart created with [[Ronald Reagan|President Reagan]]'s Pollster, [[Richard Wirthlin]], an influential polling base on Wall Street.\n\nStewart helped to manage a task force created by then New York Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] and then New York Mayor [[David Norman Dinkins]] that resolved the multiyear impasse about what to do with $7,000,000,000 of federal highway money left over when the [[West Side Highway|Westway Project]] was halted.<ref>\"Final Report of the West Side Task Force\" 5 (State of New York, 1987).</ref>\n\n===Insurance Information Institute===\nStewart joined the [[Insurance Information Institute]] in 1989 as Executive Vice President, and in 1991 became its president and remained in that position until 2006, when he turned the Institute's leadership over to its Chief Economist, Dr. Robert P. Hartwig.<ref name=\"Friedman\">Sam Friedman, [http://www.propertycasualty360.com/2006/12/18/stewart-saves-institute-from--death-spiral \"Stewart Saves Institute from Death Spiral\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''National Underwriter'' (December 18\u201325, 2006), propertycasualty360.com; accessed December 12, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"III\">Regis Coccia, [http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/20060731/ISSUE0505/358 \"Insurance Information Institute President Sets Stage to Retire at End of Year\"], ''Business Insurance'', July 31, 2006.</ref><ref>''The Financing of Catastrophe Risk, IX'' (Kenneth Froot (ed.), University of Chicago Press, 1999.<!-- ISBN/ISSN, page(s) needed --></ref>\n\nAn important goal for Stewart in re-building the Institute was to persuade insurance companies that their reputation is ultimately determined by their market place activities and policies.<ref>Gordon Stewart, ''Can Reputations be Managed?'', The Geneva Papers, 2006, 31 (pp. 480\u201399)<!--ISBN/ISSN needed--></ref><ref>[http://www.genevaassociation.org/PDF/Geneva_Reports/GA-2012-Geneva_report%5b6%5d.pdf Gordon Stewart, \"Retirement Security in the United States \u2013 A National Challenge\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120235235/http://www.genevaassociation.org/PDF/Geneva_Reports/GA-2012-Geneva_report%5B6%5D.pdf |date=2013-01-20 }}, ''The Geneva Reports No. 6: Risk and Insurance Research \u2013 Addressing the Challenge of Global Aging \u2013 Funding Issues and Insurance Solutions'', Patrick M. Liedtke and Kai-Uwe Schanz (eds; June 1012)<!-- ISBN/ISSN needed --></ref> From the time Stewart took over the Institute, the overall public approval rating of the industry rose from under 35% to above 60%.<ref name=\"Friedman\"/><ref name=\"III\"/>\n\n===Post-Insurance Information Institute===\nIn 1995, Stewart was invited by the industry-CEO membership of the Switzerland-based think-tank, [[Geneva Association|The Geneva Association for the Study of Insurance Economics]], to chair the Geneva Association's first Communications Council, and to later become the North American Liaison in charge of managing The Geneva Association's presence in the United States.<ref>''Insurance and September 11 \u2013 One Year After'', pp. 231\u201338, Patrick M. Liedtke & Christophe Courbage (eds.), The Geneva Association, 2002.<!-- ISBN/ISSN needed --></ref>\n\n===Philipstown Dot Info===\nIn 2010, Stewart created an online newspaper Philipstown Dot Info. The paper's purpose is to create a working model for community-supported journalism similar to listener-supported radio that can be replicated in municipalities all across the country.  The launch of the paper followed the buyout and redirection of the pre-existing and longstanding local newspaper by Roger Ailes, Chairman of [[Fox News]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Boyer|first=Peter J.|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2011/01/31/110131fa_fact_boyer|title=Our Towns Dept: Fox Among the Chickens|publisher=The New Yorker|date=2011-01-31|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref><ref>[[Gabriel Sherman]], ''[[The Loudest Voice in the Room: How the Brilliant, Bombastic Roger Ailes Built Fox News \u2013 and Divided a Country]]'' (Random House, 2014) pp. 358\u201361, 366\u201367, 392.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref><ref>Jacob Weisberg, \"Networker: Gabriel Sherman's ''Loudest Voice in the Room''\", ''The New York Times'' Sunday Book Review, January 12, 2014.</ref>\n\nPhilipstown Dot Info received a 2011 Standard of Excellence Award from the New Media Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmediaawards.org/websiteawards/2011/philipstown.html|title=Philipstown.info \u2013 2011 New Media Awards Winner|publisher=Newmediaawards.org|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> In 2012, Philipstown Dot Info introduced its weekly print publication, called \"The Paper\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Sherman|first=Gabriel|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intel/2012/05/roger-ailes-is-in-an-upstate-newspaper-war.html|title=Roger Ailes Is in an Upstate Newspaper War|publisher=Daily Intelligencer|date=2010-07-04|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2013, Stewart was awarded Outstanding Business Person of the Year by the [[Cold Spring, New York]] Chamber of Commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coldspringareachamber.org/awards.html |title=Cold Spring Chamber of Commerce \u2013 Awards |publisher=Coldspringareachamber.org |date=2013-03-21 |accessdate=2014-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228191136/http://www.coldspringareachamber.org/awards.html |archivedate=2014-02-28 }}</ref>\n\nIn September, 2009, Stewart was asked by ''[[The New York Times]]'' to write a response to President Obama's First Inauguration.<ref>[http://roomfordebate.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/the-speech-the-experts-critique Review of the Obama inauguration], roomfordebate.blogs.nytimes.com, January 20, 2009; accessed November 27, 2014.</ref> In September 2012, Stewart was asked by [[CNN]] to write a response to [[Michelle Obama]]'s speech to the [[Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/09/05/opinion/stewart-michelle-obama/index.html|title=Will Michelle Obama's speech change history?|publisher=CNN|date=2012-09-05|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref> In February 2013, Stewart was asked by CNN to write a response to President Obama's second inaugural address.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/01/21/opinion/stewart-obama-inaugural-speech|title=Obama finally meets Machiavelli|publisher=CNN|date=2013-01-21|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref>\n\n===International Insurance Industry Century of \"Game Changers\"===\nIn 2013, Stewart was named by the Council of Insurance Agents & Brokers, an association for commercial insurance intermediaries, as one of the international insurance industry's of the last 100 years \u2013 Stewart was  recognized for his work with the Insurance Information Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ciab100.com/gamechangers/game-changer-gordon-stewart |title=Game Changer \u2013 Gordon Stewart &#124; CIAB100: The 100th Anniversary of The Council for Insurance Agents and Brokers |publisher=CIAB100 |accessdate=2014-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304112720/http://ciab100.com/gamechangers/game-changer-gordon-stewart |archivedate=2014-03-04 }}</ref>\n\n==Memberships==\nStewart was a longstanding Member of the [[Writers Guild of America]], the [[Judson Welliver Society|Judson Welliver Society of Senior Presidential Speechwriters]] (for which he acted as Secretary since its founding by [[William Safire]] during [[Ronald Reagan|President Reagan]]'s first Administration),<ref>Carol Gelderman, ''All the President's Words'', p. 129 Walker & Co., 1997.<!-- ISBN/ISSN needed --></ref> the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], the [[Century Association]], the [[Phi Beta Kappa]] Society, and the [[Yale Club]].<ref>[http://bios.marquiswhoswho.com/gordon_curran_stewart/retired_insurance_institute_executive/5383003 Profile of Gordon C. Stewart] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140312205929/http://bios.marquiswhoswho.com/gordon_curran_stewart/retired_insurance_institute_executive/5383003 |date=2014-03-12 }}, marquiswhoswho.com; accessed November 27, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nStewart died on November 26, 2014, aged 75. He had suffered from [[emphysema]].<ref name=\"death\"/>\n\n==Selection of Creative Works==\n\n===Screenwriter===\n* ''The Store'' (1978)\n* ''Joey'' (1978)\n* ''Gallery'' (1978)\n\n===Theatre Director===\n* ''[[The Elephant Man]]'' (U.S. debut, 1977)\n* ''Jesse'' (1975)\n* ''Cowboy Mouth'' (1976)\n* ''Sleep'' (1977)\n\n===Film Director===\n* ''The Blazers'' (1975)\n\n===Music Conductor===\n* ''The Messiah'' (2013)\n* ''Beggar's Opera'' (1969, 2012)\n* ''West Side Story'' (1970)\n\n==Personal life==\nStewart married Zanne Early in 1995; they had one child, a daughter, Katarina.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Empty section|date=October 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Gordon Curran}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American theatre directors]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:American male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from emphysema]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Laboratory Schools alumni]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name= Gordon Stewart\n| birth_name= Gordon Curran Stewart\n| birth_date= July 22, 1939\n| birth_place= [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date = November 26, 2014 (aged 75)\n| death_place = [[Garrison, New York]], U.S.<ref name=\"death\">[http://philipstown.info/2014/11/28/gordon-stewart-founder-gone Notice of death of Gordon C. Stewart], philipstown.info, November 28, 2014; accessed December 12, 2014.</ref>\n| education= [[University of Chicago Laboratory Schools]], [[Oberlin College#College of Arts & Sciences|Oberlin College of Arts and Sciences]], [[University of Chicago]], [[University of Vienna]], [[Yale School of Drama]]\n| occupation= Vice Chairman of the International Insurance Society, Publisher of the Philipstown Dot Info Newspaper, Founder of The Next Deal, Inc.\n| known_for= Deputy Chief Speechwriter to President Carter 1978\u20131981, Vice President of American Stock Exchange 1982\u20131989, President of Insurance Information Institute 1991\u20132006, North American Liaison for The Geneva Association 1995\u20132012, and Vice Chairman of the International Insurance Society 2012\u2013present.\n|spouse= Zanne Early (1995\u20132014; his death) \n|children =1}}\n\n'''Gordon Curran Stewart''' (July 22, 1939 \u2013 November 26, 2014)<ref name=\"death\"/> was an American speechwriter, academic, businessman and publisher.\n\nStewart was:\n* Deputy Chief Speechwriter to [[Jimmy Carter|President Jimmy Carter]]<ref>[https://newrepublic.com/tags/gordon-stewart Profile], newrepublic.com; accessed November 28, 2014.</ref>\n* President of the [[Insurance Information Institute]]<ref>[http://www.iii.org/press-release/gordon-stewart-to-retire-from-iii-december-31robert-p-hartwig-to-become-president-071106 \"Gordon Stewart profile], iii.org, Insurance Information Institute website; accessed November 28, 2014.</ref>\n* North American Liaison for [[The Geneva Association]]\n* Chairman of The Geneva Association Communications Council\n* Executive for Policy and Programs to New York Mayor [[John Lindsay]]\n* Head of Public Affairs for [[Arthur Levitt]] at the [[American Stock Exchange]]\n* Member of the [[Defense Science Board]]\n\nHe wrote on political and economic topics for the [[International Association for the Study of Insurance Economics]], ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[US News & World Report]]'', and [[CNN]].\n\n==Early life==\nStewart was born in Chicago in 1939 to Henry Stewart and Evangeline (n\u00e9e Williams) Stewart. His father was born in Scotland and emigrated to the United States at the age of 26, where he became a Presbyterian minister and social worker/organizer in the Chicago neighborhoods. Stewart's mother, Evangeline, worked as a [[University of Chicago]] librarian, and this, coupled with the help of a scholarship, allowed Stewart to enter the [[University of Chicago Laboratory Schools]], where he remained into his high school years and where he was Student Body President. {{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n==Education==\nStewart received his Bachelor of Arts degree from the [[Oberlin College#College of Arts & Sciences|Oberlin College of Arts and Sciences]] (as the full four-year George F. Baker Scholar having been accepted at the age of 16), where he focused on history and music.  He returned to the University of Chicago to work on a PhD. in European History.  He studied music and drama at the [[University of Vienna]] in Austria, and then received an MFA in Directing from [[Yale School of Drama]]. In his last year at the Yale School of Drama, he was admitted as a doctoral candidate in comparative literature, which led to his first position as an instructor of English and theatre at [[Amherst College]]. {{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n==Career==\n\n===Pre-White House===\nStewart's first political job was as a ten-year-old poll-watcher in Chicago's 5th Ward which staunchly but futilely opposed the political machine of [[Richard J. Daley]]. His next was at the University of Chicago Laboratory Schools where he was Student Body President. As a student at [[Oberlin College]], he won its only all-school election, and spent several months traveling in and writing about West Africa in the days before the [[Peace Corps]] was founded. He left teaching at [[Amherst College]] to begin a career in drama and politics in New York. While he was directing plays, he worked as Director of Communications for Business Communications for the Arts. There he wrote his first article for a noted public figure, former US Treasury Secretary [[C. Douglas Dillon]], followed by speeches for [[Katharine Graham]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[William S. Paley]] of [[CBS]], and [[Arnold Gingrich]], the founder of ''Esquire Magazine'', who introduced him to New York Mayor [[John Lindsay]], which led to his position as Chief Speechwriter and Executive Assistant to the Mayor from 1971\u201373. {{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nFollowing his time in City Hall, Stewart was Director of Policy for [[Howard J. Samuels]]'s run for the Governorship of New York in 1974, and also wrote speeches for other [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] campaigns, including [[Jimmy Carter]]'s successful run for the Presidency of the United States in 1976. During this time, Stewart also wrote and directed theatre in New York and London.<ref>John Willis, ''Theatre World, #134, Crown Publishers, 1977.<!-- ISBN/ISSN, page(s) needed --></ref>\n\nHe worked as a screenwriter in Los Angeles, where he became a lifelong friend of [[Philip Dunne (writer)|Philip Ives Dunne]], the first screenwriter to receive a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], and a strong and vocal opponent of the [[Hollywood blacklist|Hollywood Blacklisting]] of the 1950s. Stewart gave the dedication speech for the [https://web.archive.org/web/20130407173125/http://www.wga.org/theater/theater.html Writer's Guild Theatre] when it was named in Dunne's honor.\n\nIn Hollywood, Stewart was asked to direct '''[[The Elephant Man (play)|The Elephant Man]]'' in its Broadway debut in New York.<ref name=\"Mattson\">Kevin Mattson, \"What the Heck Are You Up To, Mr. President? Jimmy Carter, America's \"Malaise\", and the Speech That Should Have Changed the Country\" (Bloomsbury, 2009)</ref> Soon after, he was appointed Deputy Chief Speechwriter to [[Jimmy Carter|President Carter]].<ref name=\"death\"/>\n\n===White House===\nCarter's Chief Speechwriter [[Hendrik Hertzberg]] invited Stewart to join the White House in 1978 as the President's Deputy Chief Speechwriter.<ref>\"Presidential Speechwriting\", pp. 169\u201388 (Kurt Ritter, ed., Texas A&M University Press, 2003).</ref><ref name=\"RobertSchlesinger\">Robert Schlesinger, ''White House Ghosts, Presidents and their Speechwriters from FDR to George W. Bush'' (Simon & Schuster, 2008), pp. 301\u201304.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref><ref name=\"mattson\">Kevin Mattson, ''\"What the Heck Are You Up To, Mr. President? Jimmy Carter, America's 'Malaise', and the Speech That Should Have Changed the Country\"'' (Bloomsbury, 2009), pp. 63\u201364.<!-- ISBN/ISSN needed --></ref> Stewart collaborated with Hertzberg on virtually all the major speeches of the Carter Presidency from 1978 onwards, including the landmark presidential address, the [[Oval Office]] [[Malaise speech|\"Crisis of Confidence\" talk of July 15, 1979]].<ref name=\"Mattson\"/><ref name=\"RobertSchlesinger\"/><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/15/opinion/15stewart.html Gordon Stewart, ''Carter's Speech Therapy''], ''The New York Times'', July 14, 2009.</ref>\n\nStewart was directly involved in multiple Presidential projects including the [[Strategic Arms Limitation Talks]] (SALT II), energy, fiscal and monetary policy, human rights issues, the response to the [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan]], the first visit to the White House by a Pope in United States history by [[Pope John Paul II]] in 1979, three State of the Union addresses, and the farewell speech of President Carter to the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmycarterlibrary.gov/documents/speeches/farewell.phtml|title=President Jimmy Carter's Farewell Address|publisher=Jimmycarterlibrary.gov|accessdate=2014-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211221648/http://www.jimmycarterlibrary.gov/documents/speeches/farewell.phtml|archive-date=2013-12-11|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Post White House===\nFollowing his time in the White House, Stewart continued his work in politics as a director of the [[New York Urban Coalition]], and as an advisor to various business, government, and academic forums including the [[Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget]], the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], the American Business Conference in Washington DC the [[International Commission for Central American Recovery and Development]], the [[Council on Competitiveness]], and the [[Defence Science Board]].<ref>\"The Report on the International Commission for Central American Recovery\", page ix, Duke University, 1989.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref><ref>Sally Bedell Smith, ''The Life of Pamela Churchill Harriman'', p. 355, Simon & Schuster, 1996.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref>\n\n===American Stock Exchange===\nFrom 1982\u201389, Stewart served as Vice President of the [[American Stock Exchange]] under [[Arthur Levitt Jr.]]<ref>Arthur Levitt & Gordon Stewart, \"Can American Business Compete?\", ''GLOBAL COMPETIVENESS: GETTING THE U.S. BACK ON TRACK'', pp. 271\u2013298 (Martin K. Starr ed., Norton 1988)</ref><ref>Daniel Yergin, ''Global Insecurity'' (Houghton Mifflin, 1982); {{ISBN|9780395305171}} (back cover citation)<!-- page(s) needed --></ref>  Responsible for the external affairs of the Exchange, Stewart created with [[Ronald Reagan|President Reagan]]'s Pollster, [[Richard Wirthlin]], an influential polling base on Wall Street.\n\nStewart helped to manage a task force created by then New York Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] and then New York Mayor [[David Norman Dinkins]] that resolved the multiyear impasse about what to do with $7,000,000,000 of federal highway money left over when the [[West Side Highway|Westway Project]] was halted.<ref>\"Final Report of the West Side Task Force\" 5 (State of New York, 1987).</ref>\n\n===Insurance Information Institute===\nStewart joined the [[Insurance Information Institute]] in 1989 as Executive Vice President, and in 1991 became its President and remained in that position until 2006, when he turned the Institute's leadership over to its Chief Economist, Dr. Robert P. Hartwig.<ref name=\"Friedman\">Sam Friedman, [http://www.propertycasualty360.com/2006/12/18/stewart-saves-institute-from--death-spiral \"Stewart Saves Institute from Death Spiral\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''National Underwriter'' (December 18\u201325, 2006), propertycasualty360.com; accessed December 12, 2014.</ref><ref name=\"III\">Regis Coccia, [http://www.businessinsurance.com/article/20060731/ISSUE0505/358 \"Insurance Information Institute President Sets Stage to Retire at End of Year\"], ''Business Insurance'', July 31, 2006.</ref><ref>''The Financing of Catastrophe Risk, IX'' (Kenneth Froot (ed.), University of Chicago Press, 1999.<!-- ISBN/ISSN, page(s) needed --></ref>\n\nAn important goal for Stewart in re-building the Institute was to persuade insurance companies that their reputation is ultimately determined by their market place activities and policies.<ref>Gordon Stewart, ''Can Reputations be Managed?'', The Geneva Papers, 2006, 31 (pp. 480\u201399)<!--ISBN/ISSN needed--></ref><ref>[http://www.genevaassociation.org/PDF/Geneva_Reports/GA-2012-Geneva_report%5b6%5d.pdf Gordon Stewart, \"Retirement Security in the United States \u2013 A National Challenge\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120235235/http://www.genevaassociation.org/PDF/Geneva_Reports/GA-2012-Geneva_report%5B6%5D.pdf |date=2013-01-20 }}, ''The Geneva Reports No. 6: Risk and Insurance Research \u2013 Addressing the Challenge of Global Aging \u2013 Funding Issues and Insurance Solutions'', Patrick M. Liedtke and Kai-Uwe Schanz (eds; June 1012)<!-- ISBN/ISSN needed --></ref> From the time Stewart took over the Institute, the overall public approval rating of the industry rose from under 35% to above 60%.<ref name=\"Friedman\"/><ref name=\"III\"/>\n\n===Post-Insurance Information Institute===\nIn 1995, Stewart was invited by the industry-CEO membership of the Switzerland-based think-tank, [[Geneva Association|The Geneva Association for the Study of Insurance Economics]], to chair the Geneva Association's first Communications Council, and to later become the North American Liaison in charge of managing The Geneva Association's presence in the United States.<ref>''Insurance and September 11 \u2013 One Year After'', pp. 231\u201338, Patrick M. Liedtke & Christophe Courbage (eds.), The Geneva Association, 2002.<!-- ISBN/ISSN needed --></ref>\n\n===Philipstown Dot Info===\nIn 2010, Stewart created an online newspaper Philipstown Dot Info. The paper's purpose is to create a working model for community-supported journalism similar to listener-supported radio that can be replicated in municipalities all across the country.  The launch of the paper followed the buyout and redirection of the pre-existing and longstanding local newspaper by Roger Ailes, Chairman of [[Fox News]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Boyer|first=Peter J.|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2011/01/31/110131fa_fact_boyer|title=Our Towns Dept: Fox Among the Chickens|publisher=The New Yorker|date=2011-01-31|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref><ref>[[Gabriel Sherman]], ''[[The Loudest Voice in the Room: How the Brilliant, Bombastic Roger Ailes Built Fox News \u2013 and Divided a Country]]'' (Random House, 2014) pp. 358\u201361, 366\u201367, 392.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref><ref>Jacob Weisberg, \"Networker: Gabriel Sherman's ''Loudest Voice in the Room''\", ''The New York Times'' Sunday Book Review, January 12, 2014.</ref>\n\nPhilipstown Dot Info received a 2011 Standard of Excellence Award from the New Media Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmediaawards.org/websiteawards/2011/philipstown.html|title=Philipstown.info \u2013 2011 New Media Awards Winner|publisher=Newmediaawards.org|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> In 2012, Philipstown Dot Info introduced its weekly print publication, called \"The Paper\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Sherman|first=Gabriel|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intel/2012/05/roger-ailes-is-in-an-upstate-newspaper-war.html|title=Roger Ailes Is in an Upstate Newspaper War|publisher=Daily Intelligencer|date=2010-07-04|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2013, Stewart was awarded Outstanding Business Person of the Year by the [[Cold Spring, New York]] Chamber of Commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coldspringareachamber.org/awards.html |title=Cold Spring Chamber of Commerce \u2013 Awards |publisher=Coldspringareachamber.org |date=2013-03-21 |accessdate=2014-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228191136/http://www.coldspringareachamber.org/awards.html |archivedate=2014-02-28 }}</ref>\n\nIn September, 2009, Stewart was asked by ''[[The New York Times]]'' to write a response to President Obama's First Inauguration.<ref>[http://roomfordebate.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/the-speech-the-experts-critique Review of the Obama inauguration], roomfordebate.blogs.nytimes.com, January 20, 2009; accessed November 27, 2014.</ref> In September 2012, Stewart was asked by [[CNN]] to write a response to [[Michelle Obama]]'s speech to the [[Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/09/05/opinion/stewart-michelle-obama/index.html|title=Will Michelle Obama's speech change history?|publisher=CNN|date=2012-09-05|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref> In February 2013, Stewart was asked by CNN to write a response to President Obama's second inaugural address.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/01/21/opinion/stewart-obama-inaugural-speech|title=Obama finally meets Machiavelli|publisher=CNN|date=2013-01-21|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref>\n\n===International Insurance Industry Century of \"Game Changers\"===\nIn 2013, Stewart was named by the Council of Insurance Agents & Brokers, an association for commercial insurance intermediaries, as one of the international insurance industry's of the last 100 years \u2013 Stewart was  recognized for his work with the Insurance Information Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ciab100.com/gamechangers/game-changer-gordon-stewart |title=Game Changer \u2013 Gordon Stewart &#124; CIAB100: The 100th Anniversary of The Council for Insurance Agents and Brokers |publisher=CIAB100 |accessdate=2014-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304112720/http://ciab100.com/gamechangers/game-changer-gordon-stewart |archivedate=2014-03-04 }}</ref>\n\n==Memberships==\nStewart was a longstanding Member of the [[Writers Guild of America]], the [[Judson Welliver Society|Judson Welliver Society of Senior Presidential Speechwriters]] (for which he acted as Secretary since its founding by [[William Safire]] during [[Ronald Reagan|President Reagan]]'s first Administration),<ref>Carol Gelderman, ''All the President's Words'', p. 129 Walker & Co., 1997.<!-- ISBN/ISSN needed --></ref> the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], the [[Century Association]], the [[Phi Beta Kappa]] Society, and the [[Yale Club]].<ref>[http://bios.marquiswhoswho.com/gordon_curran_stewart/retired_insurance_institute_executive/5383003 Profile of Gordon C. Stewart] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140312205929/http://bios.marquiswhoswho.com/gordon_curran_stewart/retired_insurance_institute_executive/5383003 |date=2014-03-12 }}, marquiswhoswho.com; accessed November 27, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nStewart died on November 26, 2014, aged 75. He had suffered from [[emphysema]].<ref name=\"death\"/>\n\n==Selection of Creative Works==\n\n===Screenwriter===\n* ''The Store'' (1978)\n* ''Joey'' (1978)\n* ''Gallery'' (1978)\n\n===Theatre Director===\n* ''[[The Elephant Man]]'' (U.S. debut, 1977)\n* ''Jesse'' (1975)\n* ''Cowboy Mouth'' (1976)\n* ''Sleep'' (1977)\n\n===Film Director===\n* ''The Blazers'' (1975)\n\n===Music Conductor===\n* ''The Messiah'' (2013)\n* ''Beggar's Opera'' (1969, 2012)\n* ''West Side Story'' (1970)\n\n==Personal life==\nStewart married Zanne Early in 1995; they had one child, a daughter, Katarina.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Empty section|date=October 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Gordon Curran}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American theatre directors]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:American male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from emphysema]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Laboratory Schools alumni]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: Student Body President \u2192 student body president (2),typo(s) fixed: President \u2192 president", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gordon_Curran_Stewart"}
