{"title_page": "Patrick Mara", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name                = Patrick Mara\n|honorific-suffix    =\n|image               = Marahs.jpg\n|alma_mater          = [[Babson College]],<br/> [[Marist College]]\n|occupation          = [[Consultant]]\n|office              = [[Board of Education|State Board of Education]], [[Neighborhoods in Washington, D.C.#Ward 1|Ward One]]\n|term_start          = 2011\n|term_end            = 2015\n|predecessor         = Dotti Love Wade<ref name= election2010/>\n|successor           = Laura Wilson Phelan<ref>{{cite news |title= D.C. State Board of Education has three new members |first= Michael Alison |last=Chandler |date= November 5, 2014 |work= The Washington Post |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/dc-state-board-of-education-has-three-new-members/2014/11/05/531b5e18-6502-11e4-836c-83bc4f26eb67_story.html }}</ref>\n|website             = {{URL|http://www.patrickmara.com}}\n|residence           = [[Columbia Heights (Washington, D.C.)|Columbia Heights, Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=livechat>{{cite web |title= Live chat with Patrick Mara |first= David |last= Alpert |date= February 2, 2011 |work= Greater Greater Washington |url= http://greatergreaterwashington.org/post/9076/live-chat-with-patrick-mara/ }}</ref>\n|party = [[US Republican Party|Republican]] \n}}\n\n'''Patrick Mara''' is a former elected member of the [[District of Columbia Public Schools|District of Columbia Board of Education]].\n\n==Early years==\nMara is originally from [[Rhode Island]].<ref name=torun/> He earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] in political science and environmental science at [[Marist College]].<ref name= canpat>{{cite news |title= Try and Try and Try Again|first= Alan |last= Suderman |work= Washington City Paper |date= April 3, 2013 |url= http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/looselips/2013/04/03/try-and-try-and-try-again/ }}</ref> While at Marist, Mara was student body president<ref>{{cite news |title=Mara administration takes helm with transition dinner |first=Daryl |last=Richard |work=The Circle |date=April 18, 1996 |publisher=Marist College |url=http://library.marist.edu/archives/Circle/1996/1996_4_18.pdf }}</ref> Mara later served as President of the Marist College Alumni Executive Board and the Alumni Representative to the Marist College Board of Trustees.<ref>{{citation |title=Alumni Association Executive Board |work=Marist College |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |url=http://www.marist.edu/alumni/board.html }}</ref> He graduated with a [[Master of Business Administration]] in entrepreneurship from [[Babson College]].<ref name= canpat/>\n\n==Political career==\nMara was a staffer for [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John H. Chafee]], working on environmental issues.<ref name= canpat/>\n\nIn 2008, Mara defeated<ref>{{citation |title=Schwartz falls to Mara |work=The Examiner|location=Washington, D.C. |first=Michael |last=Neibauer |date=September 10, 2008|url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/politics/schwartz-falls-mara }}</ref> incumbent [[Carol Schwartz]] in the Republican primary for an at-large seat on the [[Council of the District of Columbia]]. The ''[[Washington Blade]]'' endorsed Mara, noting his support for same-sex marriage and other stands in support of civil rights.<ref name=\"washblade.com\">http://www.washblade.com/2008/10-31/view/columns/13533.cfm</ref> ''The Washington Post'' endorsed Mara in the Republican primary<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/02/AR2008090202444.html | work=The Washington Post | title=The D.C. Council Primary | date=2008-09-03 | accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref> and in the General Election.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/10/22/AR2008102202987.html | work=The Washington Post | title=For D.C. Council | date=2008-10-23 | accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/10/30/AR2008103003632.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Bucking a Tide in D.C | date=2008-10-31 | accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref> Democrat [[Kwame R. Brown]] and independent [[Michael A. Brown (Washington D.C. politician)|Michael A. Brown]] won the general election.\n\nIn 2010, Mara won the Ward One seat on the District of Columbia [[Board of Education|State Board of Education]] with 53 percent of the vote.<ref>{{citation |work=DC BOEE |title=DC Board Of Elections And Ethics: Election Results |url= http://www.dcboee.org/election_info/election_results/general_election_results/2010 |accessdate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' endorsed Mara in the election.<ref>{{citation |title=For D.C. State Board of Education |work=The Washington Post |format=editorial |date=October 25, 2010 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/10/24/AR2010102402494.html }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Mara ran in a [[special election]] for the [[at-large]] seat on the Council of the District of Columbia.<ref name=torun>{{cite news |title=Patrick Mara to run for D.C. Council at-large seat |first=Mike |last=DeBonis |work=The Washington Post |date=January 19, 2011|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/debonis/2011/01/patrick_mara_to_run_for_dc_cou.html }}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' endorsed Mara in the 2011 special election for At-Large D.C. Council.<ref>{{citation |title=Patrick Mara for an at-large seat on the D.C. Council |work=The Washington Post |format=editorial |date=April 12, 2011 |url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2011-04-12/opinions/35261845_1_council-member-charter-schools-school-reforms }}</ref> Mara came in second behind [[Vincent Orange]].<ref name= 2011s/>\n\nMara was a board member at DC Vote from 2011 to 2013.\n\nMara was a candidate in the special election for the at-large seat on the Council of the District of Columbia in 2013. He was endorsed by ''The Washington Post''.<ref name=\"Board\">{{citation |work=Washington Post |title=Patrick Mara for D.C. Council |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/patrick-mara-for-dc-council/2013/03/21/e9beda84-8db8-11e2-9f54-f3fdd70acad2_story.html |accessdate=March 21, 2013 |first=Editorial |last=Board |date=March 21, 2013}}</ref> [[New Jersey Governor]] [[Chris Christie]] [[robocall]]ed Republicans in the District for Mara.<ref>{{cite news |title= Opening Act: Pat Mara |first= David |last= Weigel |work= Slate |date= April 24, 2013 |url= http://www.slate.com/blogs/weigel/2013/04/24/opening_act_pat_mara.html }}</ref> The D.C. chapter of the [[Sierra Club]] and the District of Columbia Chamber of Commerce endorsed Mara in the special election. Democratic Councilmember [[Anita Bonds]] won the election; Mara came in third place.<ref name= 2013s/>\n\nIn 2014, Mara decided not to run for reelection to the District of Columbia State Board of Education.<ref>{{cite news |title= Meet the Ward 1 candidates for D.C. State Board of Education |first= Michael Alison |last= Chandler |date= October 29, 2014 |work= The Washington Post |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/local/wp/2014/10/29/meet-the-ward-1-candidates-for-d-c-state-board-of-education/ }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, Mara was appointed executive director of the [[District of Columbia Republican Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |title= State GOP Leadership: District of Columbia Leadership: Patrick Mara, Executive Director |work= Republican National Committee |accessdate= September 19, 2015 |url= https://gop.com/leaders/executive-director-patrick-mara-dc }}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nMara owns The Dolan Group LLC,<ref>{{cite web |title= Dolan Group, LLC (The) - Initial File Number: L42183 |work= District of Columbia Department of Consumer and Regulatory Affairs |publisher= Government of the District of Columbia |accessdate= September 19, 2015 |url= https://corp.dcra.dc.gov/BizEntity.aspx/ViewContact?bizEntityContactId=436564&currentTabConfigurationId=468 }}</ref> a business consulting firm in Washington, D.C.<ref name= election2010>{{citation |work=Washington Post |title=Election 2010: D.C. Board of Education, Ward 1 |url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/elections/2010/dc/board-member/1757/ |accessdate=November 7, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101105204541/http://projects.washingtonpost.com/elections/2010/dc/board-member/1757 |archivedate= November 5, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nMara has served on the [[board of directors]] of One World Education<ref>{{citation |title=Board of Directors |work=One World Education |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |url=http://www.oneworldeducation.org/about-owed/board-of-directors }}</ref> and the Columbia Heights Day Initiative.<ref>{{citation |title=About the Annual Columbia Heights Day Festival |work=Columbia Heights Day Initiative |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |url=http://www.cohiday.org/about.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120309221750/http://www.cohiday.org/about.html |archivedate= March 9, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nMara is a board member of College & Career Connections<ref>{{cite web |url= http://collegeandcareerconnections.org/about/leadership_board.shtml |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101002162337/http://collegeandcareerconnections.org/about/leadership_board.shtml |archivedate= October 2, 2010 |work= College & Career Connections |title= Leadership: Board of Directors }}</ref> and [[Washington Latin Public Charter School]].<ref name= latin>{{cite web |work= Washington Latin Public Charter School |accessdate= September 19, 2015 |title= Board of Governors |url= http://latinpcs.org/about/our-team/board/ }}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n===2008===\n{{Election box begin no change\n  | title     = '''2008 [[Council of the District of Columbia]], [[At-large|At Large]], [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Primary election|Primary]]'''<ref name=2008p>{{cite web |title=Certified Results, Primary Election, 2008  |work= District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date=September 26, 2008 |url= https://www.dcboee.org/election_info/election_results/election_result_new/results_final.asp?electionid=1&prev=0&result_type=3&party=-87 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Patrick Mara\n  |votes      = 2,370\n  |percentage = 59\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Carol Schwartz]]\n  |votes      = 1,646\n  |percentage = 41\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Write-in\n  |votes      = 19\n  |percentage = 0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n  | title     = 2008 [[Council of the District of Columbia]], [[At-large|At Large]], [[General Election]]<ref name=2008g>{{cite web |title=Certified Results, Primary Election, 2008  |work=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date=November 24, 2008 |url= https://www.dcboee.org/election_info/election_results/election_result_new/results_final.asp?electionid=1&prev=0&result_type=3&party=-87 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Kwame R. Brown]]\n  |votes      = 172,272\n  |percentage = 48\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Independent (politician)\n  |candidate  = [[Michael A. Brown (Washington D.C. politician)|Michael A. Brown]]\n  |votes      = 71,720\n  |percentage = 20\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Patrick Mara\n  |votes      = 37,447\n  |percentage = 10\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = D.C. Statehood Green Party\n  |candidate  = David Schwartzman\n  |votes      = 18,596\n  |percentage = 5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change  \n  |party      = Independent (politician)\n  |candidate  = Mark H. Long\n  |votes      = 14,603\n  |percentage = 4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Independent (politician)  \n  |candidate  = Dee Hunter\n  |votes      = 7,311\n  |percentage = 2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n  |party      = \n  |candidate  = Write-in ''(including Carol Schwartz)''\n  |votes      = 39,493\n  |percentage = 11\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2010===\n{{Election box begin no change\n  | title     = 2010 State Board of Education, Ward One, [[General Election]]<ref name=2010g>{{cite web |title=Certified Results, General Election, 2010  |work=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date=November 19, 2010 |url= https://www.dcboee.org/election_info/election_results/general_election_results/2010 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Non-partisan\n  |candidate  = Patrick Mara\n  |votes      = 6,731\n  |percentage = 53\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Non-partisan\n  |candidate  = Dotti Love Wade\n  |votes      = 5,856\n  |percentage = 46\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Non-partisan\n  |candidate  = Write-in\n  |votes      = 150\n  |percentage = 1\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===2011===\n{{Election box begin no change\n  | title     = 2011 [[Council of the District of Columbia]], [[At-large|At Large]], [[Special Election]]<ref name=2011s>{{cite web |title=Certified Results, Special Election, 2011 |work=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date= April 26, 2011 |url= https://www.dcboee.org/election_info/election_results/2011/April-26-Special-Election/ }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= April 26, 2011 Special Election Voter Guide |work= District of Columbia Board of Elections |date= April 13, 2011 |url= https://www.dcboee.org/popup.asp?url=/pdf_files/nr_963.pdf }}</ref> }}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party lin